# Input Validation: Use Zod in Every Server Action

All data posted to Server Actions **must** be validated with Zod before touching the database. Server Actions must accept a **TypeScript type** as their argument — never `FormData`.

## Pattern

```ts
// ✅ GOOD — typed argument + Zod validation before writing
"use server";
import { z } from "zod";
import { auth } from "@clerk/nextjs/server";
import { db } from "@/lib/db";
import { decks } from "@/lib/schema";

const createDeckSchema = z.object({
  title: z.string().trim().min(1, "Title is required").max(100),
});

type CreateDeckInput = z.infer<typeof createDeckSchema>;

export async function createDeck(input: CreateDeckInput) {
  const { userId } = await auth();
  if (!userId) throw new Error("Unauthorized");

  const parsed = createDeckSchema.safeParse(input);

  if (!parsed.success) {
    return { error: parsed.error.flatten().fieldErrors };
  }

  await db.insert(decks).values({ title: parsed.data.title, clerkUserId: userId });
}
```

```ts
// ❌ BAD — using FormData as the argument type
export async function createDeck(formData: FormData) { ... }

// ❌ BAD — writing to the database without validation
export async function createDeck(input: CreateDeckInput) {
  await db.insert(decks).values({ title: input.title, clerkUserId: userId }); // unvalidated
}
```

## Rules

- Server Actions must accept a **TypeScript type**, not `FormData`.
- Use `z.infer<typeof schema>` to derive the TypeScript type from the Zod schema — no duplicate type definitions.
- Always use `safeParse` (not `parse`) so errors are returned, not thrown.
- Define schemas as `const` outside the action function.
- Use `parsed.data` (not the original input) when passing values to Drizzle.
- Return `{ error: ... }` on validation failure so the UI can display field-level errors.
